(119, 'blog.element', '{\"has_image\":[\"1\"],\"title\":\"Even gardens have a carbon footprint. Here\'s how to reduce the climate impact of urban farming\",\"description\":\"<p dir=\\\"ltr\\\" style=\\\"margin-bottom:28px;color:rgb(34,34,34);font-family:\'Radio Canada\', sans-serif;font-size:16px;\\\"><span style=\\\"font-weight:700;\\\">This story is part of the Prairies Climate Change Project, a joint initiative between CBC Edmonton and CBC Saskatchewan that focuses on weather and our changing climate.<\\/span><\\/p><p dir=\\\"ltr\\\" style=\\\"margin-bottom:28px;color:rgb(34,34,34);font-family:\'Radio Canada\', sans-serif;font-size:16px;\\\">Urban gardening might seem fairly innocuous when it comes to its overall carbon footprint, but when compared to conventional agriculture, a study released earlier this year would suggest otherwise.\\u00a0<\\/p><p dir=\\\"ltr\\\" style=\\\"margin-bottom:28px;color:rgb(34,34,34);font-family:\'Radio Canada\', sans-serif;font-size:16px;\\\">The study,\\u00a0published in\\u00a0January in the science journal Nature,\\u00a0found the carbon footprint of food from urban agriculture is.<\\/p><p dir=\\\"ltr\\\" style=\\\"margin-bottom:28px;color:rgb(34,34,34);font-family:\'Radio Canada\', sans-serif;font-size:16px;\\\">But there are ways that gardeners can reduce their impact. Let\'s take a look at what\'s at play.<\\/p><h2 dir=\\\"ltr\\\" style=\\\"font-size:1.625rem;line-height:1.3;color:rgb(34,34,34);font-family:\'Radio Canada\', sans-serif;\\\">A look at the study\\u00a0<\\/h2><p dir=\\\"ltr\\\" style=\\\"margin-bottom:28px;color:rgb(34,34,34);font-family:\'Radio Canada\', sans-serif;font-size:16px;\\\">The study employed citizen science at 73 urban agriculture sites (think co-operative or collective gardens, not necessarily your backyard garden) across Europe and the United States.\\u00a0<\\/p><p dir=\\\"ltr\\\" style=\\\"margin-bottom:28px;color:rgb(34,34,34);font-family:\'Radio Canada\', sans-serif;font-size:16px;\\\">It compared food from large-scale conventional agricultural farms and urban agriculture sites, including professionally managed urban farms, individual gardens and collective gardens.<\\/p><p dir=\\\"ltr\\\" style=\\\"margin-bottom:28px;color:rgb(34,34,34);font-family:\'Radio Canada\', sans-serif;font-size:16px;\\\">\\\"The primary contributor to the carbon footprint on our sites that we studied was actually the infrastructure that was invested in growing food,\\\" said Jason Hawes, a PhD candidate in the\\u00a0University of Michigan School for Environment and Sustainability and lead author on the paper.\\u00a0<\\/p>\",\"image\":\"66cee7be8b9be1724835774.png\"}', '{\"image\":null,\"description\":null,\"social_title\":null,\"social_description\":null,\"keywords\":null}', 'basic', 'even-gardens-have-a-carbon-footprint-heres-how-to-reduce-the-climate-impact-of-urban-farming', '2024-08-28 03:02:54', '2024-08-28 03:02:57'),
(120, 'blog.element', '{\"has_image\":[\"1\"],\"title\":\"Kitchen Markets: Veggie prices shoot up\",\"description\":\"<p style=\\\"font-size:18px;line-height:26px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-family:Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:20px;margin-left:0px;\\\">The cost of various vegetables in Bangladesh has risen over the past week, making winter produce unaffordable for many. Market sources reveal that the price of staple kitchen items such as onions, garlic, and ginger has also increased. Seasonal vegetables like cauliflower and cabbage were sold at Tk 50-65 each on Thursday, while a medium-sized bottle gourd was priced at Tk 100-120, reflecting a Tk 10-20 increase per item within a week.<\\/p><p style=\\\"font-size:18px;line-height:26px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-family:Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:20px;margin-left:0px;\\\">According to a vegetable vendor at Sadeq Khan Agricultural Market, there has been a significant decrease in the supply of vegetables and potatoes this year. The prices are 30-40% higher in district vegetable hubs compared to last year due to crop losses in October and November 2023 caused by unfavorable weather conditions.<\\/p><p style=\\\"font-size:18px;line-height:26px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-family:Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:20px;margin-left:0px;\\\">A trader based in Karwanbazar, also highlighted the issue of low vegetable supplies. He mentioned that the number of vegetable-laden trucks entering Karwanbazar daily has dropped to below 240 this winter, down from a usual minimum of 400 during the peak vegetable season in January and February.<\\/p><p style=\\\"font-size:18px;line-height:26px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-family:Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:20px;margin-left:0px;\\\">Despite this, vegetable vendors claim that there is no shortage of certain winter crops, such as cauliflower, cabbage, radish, cucumber, tomato, and leafy vegetables. However, the prices remain high. The Consumers Association of Bangladesh (CAB) vice-president SM Nazer Hossain criticized the government\'s failure to maintain market checks and balances due to weak monitoring.<\\/p><p style=\\\"font-size:18px;line-height:26px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-family:Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:20px;margin-left:0px;\\\">He suggested strict monitoring to ensure market stability during the peak winter harvest season, as the rising prices have made nutritious crops too expensive for the poor.<\\/p>\",\"image\":\"66cee8168a1ca1724835862.jpg\"}', '{\"image\":null,\"description\":null,\"social_title\":null,\"social_description\":null,\"keywords\":null}', 'basic', 'kitchen-markets-veggie-prices-shoot-up', '2024-08-28 03:04:22', '2024-08-28 03:04:24'),
(121, 'blog.element', '{\"has_image\":[\"1\"],\"title\":\"Why are fruit prices soaring? In All Developing Country\",\"description\":\"<span style=\\\"color:rgb(0,0,0);font-family:times, serif;font-size:18.9px;\\\">Alongside prices of daily commodities, prices of local and imported fruits have also gone up sharply in the first week of Ramadan. In just one week, prices of all fruits increased by Tk80 to 100 per kg in the local market. In the first two days of Ramadan, prices went up by Tk20 to Tk50 per kg of different varieties of fruits at the retail level. Traders have increased the price of fruits on various pretexts, including an increase in dollar price, increase in duty, shortage in supply, credit complications, and low import.<br \\/><\\/span><br \\/><p style=\\\"padding:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:16px;margin-left:0px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-family:times, serif;font-size:18.9px;\\\">Consumers say that importers are deliberately inflating prices. Sellers say that their sales have also come down significantly<\\/p><p style=\\\"padding:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:16px;margin-left:0px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-family:times, serif;font-size:18.9px;\\\">Importers claim that the price of fruits has increased by more than 10% due to the increase in the dollar rate and hike in duty. Importers, as a result, are importing fewer amounts of fruits. Many have stopped importing completely.\\u00a0<\\/p><p style=\\\"padding:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:16px;margin-left:0px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-family:times, serif;font-size:18.9px;\\\">According to sources, duty on a handful of fruits has been increased. Then why have prices of all the fruits gone up?<\\/p><p style=\\\"padding:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:16px;margin-left:0px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-family:times, serif;font-size:18.9px;\\\">While visiting the largest wholesale market of fruit items in Dhaka, Badamtali, it was seen that prices of apples, oranges, blood oranges and grapes have increased by Tk50 to 100 per kg. At the same time, prices of bananas, papayas, guavas, stone apples and pineapples have gone up by Tk20 to 50 taka more per kg.<\\/p><p style=\\\"padding:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:16px;margin-left:0px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-family:times, serif;font-size:18.9px;\\\">Each carton of apples from Poland was being sold at Tk4,800 at Badamtoli yesterday. A week ago the same apple was selling for Tk4,300. Similarly, the price of green apples has increased from T4,200 to Tk5200 per carton. Royal gala apples were being sold at Tk5,700\\u2014up by at least Tk400 per carton.\\u00a0<\\/p><p style=\\\"padding:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:16px;margin-left:0px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-family:times, serif;font-size:18.9px;\\\">Blood oranges were sold at Tk4,250 per carton, which was Tk2,600 a week ago. Black grapes were being sold at Tk6,700 per carton. Earlier they were being sold at Tk4,600. The price of pears has gone up by Tk200 per carton. The question remains: why?<\\/p><p style=\\\"padding:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:16px;margin-left:0px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-family:times, serif;font-size:18.9px;\\\">Trader Jalal Uddin said that customs authorities have destabilized the fruit market by increasing duty without any reason. Duty on a kg of apples, oranges and blood oranges was Tk62, which is now Tk88. Similarly, duty has been fixed at Tk119 for grapes, which was Tk98. Duty on foreign fruits has now increased to 23%.<\\/p><p style=\\\"padding:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:16px;margin-left:0px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-family:times, serif;font-size:18.9px;\\\">In the retail markets, pears were sold at Tk280 per kg yesterday and grapes at Tk300. African Gala apples were being sold at Tk340 per kg. Of the local fruits, pineapple was being sold at Tk50 per piece\\u2014up from Tk30. Stone apples were being sold at Tk200 to 220 per piece\\u2014up by Tk100.\\u00a0<\\/p><p style=\\\"padding:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:16px;margin-left:0px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-family:times, serif;font-size:18.9px;\\\">The story is the same for papayas, guavas, and even watermelons. Watermelons, a juicy summer fruit, were being sold at Tk80 per kg, although it is completely locally produced.\\u00a0<\\/p><p style=\\\"padding:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:16px;margin-left:0px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-family:times, serif;font-size:18.9px;\\\">Trader Md Shaon said the prices of fruits have increased bit by bit every day for the last two weeks. Alongside increased dollar rates and duty, he blamed banks for not allowing LCs. This trader said that the demand for all varieties of fruits goes up significantly during Ramadan and the government must intervene to calm the prices down.\\u00a0<\\/p><p style=\\\"padding:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:16px;margin-left:0px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-family:times, serif;font-size:18.9px;\\\">Aleya Begum, a housewife, bought half a kg of grapes, half a kg of oranges and one kg of apples from Ray Saheb Bazar. She said that children don\\u2019t want to understand anything regarding prices. They love to eat fruits and thus there is no way but to keep buying fruits regardless of the inflated prices of fruits. Moreover, there is a huge demand for two or more fruit items for Iftar during the month of Ramadan, she added.\\u00a0<\\/p><p style=\\\"padding:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:16px;margin-left:0px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-family:times, serif;font-size:18.9px;\\\">Regarding the increase in the price of foreign fruits, Sirajul Islam, President of Bangladesh Fresh Fruits Importers Association, said that the import of fruits has decreased in the last one month. The government has imposed an additional tax on the imported fruits.\\u00a0<\\/p><p style=\\\"padding:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-left:0px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-family:times, serif;font-size:18.9px;\\\">\\u201cWe are struggling to import fruits. The price of these fruits is not likely to decrease if the duty is not reduced. If the duty is reduced, the price will be reduced. Meanwhile, a syndicate is actively inflating prices in the market,\\u201d he alleged.<\\/p>\",\"image\":\"66cee8ce5173f1724836046.jpg\"}', '{\"image\":null,\"description\":null,\"social_title\":null,\"social_description\":null,\"keywords\":null}', 'basic', 'why-are-fruit-prices-soaring-in-all-developing-country', '2024-08-28 03:07:26', '2024-08-28 04:44:50'),
